data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new built-in span conversions. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, the compiler now resolves to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)`** instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based methods, so this fails at runtime.

## Fix

Force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Either approach ensures the expression tree binds to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees can represent.
